<p id="NrzBgi">Sanderson kicked off his first series with the 2006 release of <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Mistborn-Boxed-Set-Well-Ascension/dp/125026717X/?tag=polygon05-20" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank" has-subtag="true" data-cdata='{"rewritten_url":"https://www.amazon.com/Mistborn-Boxed-Set-Well-Ascension/dp/125026717X/?ascsubtag=___pl__p_23873180__m_m-placeholder__s_s-placeholder__t_w__c_c-placeholder__r_r-placeholder__d_d-placeholder\u0026tag=polygon05-20","subtag_max_length":99,"subtag_delim_length":3,"subtag_key":"ascsubtag","subtag_data":{"ascsubtag":"___pl__p_23873180__m_m-placeholder__s_s-placeholder__t_w__c_c-placeholder__r_r-placeholder__d_d-placeholder","tag":"polygon05-20"},"encode_subtag":false}'><em>Mistborn</em></a>. Set in a grim world controlled by an immortal tyrant, it follows a young woman with great power who joins a thieving crew with a plan to change things that involves equal parts ballroom dancing and rooftop fighting. The rest of the trilogy gets progressively more political and cosmic, and Sanderson offers <em>Mistborn </em>as a starting point for veteran fantasy fans who don’t mind diving into the deep end.</p>
